<div class="home">

  <h1 class="page-heading">What is Canada.ca</h1>

<div>

    <p>We work hard to improve Canada.ca and build a better web experience for Canadians.</p>

</div>

<section>

<h2>Letter to departments</h2>
<p>On December XX, the Treasury board Secretariat sent a letter to Senior Departmental Officers (link to letter) to provide direction for the future. In this letter, all Government of Canada institutions are strongly encouraged to take the following steps:</p>

<ul>
<li> <a href="./howweimprove/letter/step1">Step 1: Create or update your public web content inventory</a></li>
<li> <a href="./howweimprove/letter/step2">Step 2: Apply the Canada.ca Content and IA Specification and Canada.ca Content Style Guide</a></li>
<li> <a href="./howweimprove/letter/step3">Step 3: Implement web and search to your top tasks</a></li>
</ul>

<h2>Optimization projects and user testing and research/h2>
<p>Website optimization is the process of testing content with users then improving it based on the results.</p>
<p>This is done to make websites as effective and user-friendly as possible.</p>

<ul>
  <li> <a href="http://www.gcpedia.gc.ca/wiki/Optimization_projects">Past, present and future optimization projects</a></li>
  <li> <a href="http://www.gcpedia.gc.ca/wiki/User_testing_and_research_-_Web_Renewal_Toolkit">User testing and research</a></li>
</ul>

</section>

